Personal Computer Operating System
Personal Computer Operating System is the most widely used operating system, applied in text processing, spreadsheets, and gaming.

Linux
Linux is a widely used open-source personal computer operating system.<SEP>Linux is an open-source operating system based on macro kernel architecture.

Embedded Operating System
Embedded Operating System is a type of operating system used in embedded systems for specific tasks.

MacOS
MacOS is a personal computer operating system developed by Apple Inc.

Smartphone Operating System
Smartphone Operating System is an operating system designed for mobile devices such as smartphones.

Windows
Windows is a commonly used personal computer operating system developed by Microsoft.<SEP>Windows is a widely used operating system developed by Microsoft, based on macro kernel architecture.

Text Processing
Text processing is the use of software to create, edit, and format text documents.

Server Operating System
Server Operating System is designed to manage network resources and provide services to other computers.

Electronic Spreadsheet
Electronic spreadsheet is a digital tool used for organizing, analyzing, and storing data in tabular form.

Gaming
Gaming refers to the use of software for interactive entertainment, commonly supported by personal computer operating systems.

Single Processor System
A single processor system can execute only one program at any given moment, leading to time-sharing execution of multiple programs.

Multitasking Environment
A multitasking environment allows multiple programs to appear to run simultaneously over a period of time, though not all at the same instant.

Parallelism
Parallelism refers to the simultaneous occurrence of two or more events at the same moment in time.<SEP>Parallelism is the ability of the system to perform multiple tasks simultaneously across different computers.<SEP>Parallelism refers to the capability of a system to perform two or more operations simultaneously at the same instant, requiring hardware support such as multiple processors or pipelines.

Multiple Processors
A system with multiple processors enables true parallel execution of multiple programs, each assigned to a separate processor.

Concurrency
Concurrency refers to the occurrence of two or more events within the same time interval, but not necessarily at the same instant.<SEP>Concurrency refers to the ability of two or more events to occur within the same time interval, achieved through time-sharing in a single processor environment.

Time-Sharing Execution
Time-sharing execution is a technique where multiple programs take turns executing on a single processor, creating the illusion of simultaneous execution.

Program Execution
Program execution refers to the running of a program instance in a computing environment.

Parallel Execution
Parallel execution involves running multiple programs or tasks simultaneously on separate processors.

User Mode
User mode is the execution state of user programs, where direct access to system resources is restricted.<SEP>User mode is a restricted system execution state in which only non-privileged instructions can be executed, preventing unauthorized access to system resources.<SEP>User mode is a CPU operational state where only non-privileged instructions can be executed, preventing direct access to system hardware.<SEP>User Mode is a CPU execution mode where user programs run with restricted privileges, unable to perform privileged operations directly.<SEP>User mode is a restricted state of the CPU in which user programs execute, preventing direct access to hardware and system resources.<SEP>User mode is a privileged execution mode in operating systems where non-essential processes run, enhancing system stability.

User Program
A user program runs in user mode and must request system services via system calls when accessing shared resources.<SEP>A User Program is an application executed in user mode that requires services from the operating system to perform tasks beyond its privileges.

System Call
A system call is an interface provided by the operating system to applications, allowing them to request services from the operating system kernel.<SEP>System Call is a programmatic way for applications to request services from the operating system, such as file operations, memory allocation, and device access.<SEP>System calls are interface mechanisms that allow programs to request services from the operating system kernel.<SEP>A System Call is a method used by a user program to request a service from the operating system, typically initiated via a trap instruction.<SEP>System call is a request by a user program to the operating system kernel for services, typically invoked via a trap instruction.

Kernel Mode
Kernel mode is a privileged execution state where the operating system kernel runs, required for handling system calls.<SEP>Kernel mode is a system execution state in which the CPU can execute all instructions, including privileged ones, ensuring full system control and security.<SEP>Kernel mode is a CPU operational state where privileged instructions can be executed, allowing full access to system resources and hardware.<SEP>Kernel Mode is a CPU execution mode with full system privileges, used by the operating system to manage hardware and system resources.<SEP>Kernel mode is a privileged state of the CPU in which the operating system kernel runs, allowing access to hardware and system resources.<SEP>Kernel mode is a privileged execution mode where the microkernel operates, managing core system functions and interactions.

System Call Number
Each system call is assigned a unique number used to identify and invoke the corresponding system call routine.

Operating System
Operating System is a system software that manages computer hardware and software resources, serving as the foundational layer between computer hardware and user applications. It is responsible for managing system resources such as the CPU, memory, storage, and input/output devices, ensuring efficient allocation and utilization. The operating system provides common services for computer programs through system calls, enabling applications to interact with the underlying hardware in a controlled and secure manner. It requires privileged instructions to perform critical functions, reflecting its central role in system security and stability. Key characteristics of an operating system include concurrency, allowing multiple processes to execute simultaneously; sharing, enabling multiple users or programs to access resources; virtualization, creating the illusion of dedicated resources; and asynchrony, managing operations that occur at unpredictable times. These features are essential for supporting multitasking, efficient program execution, and reliable system performance. Operating systems also provide user interfacesboth command-line and graphicalfor users to interact with hardware and manage system operations. Examples of operating systems include Windows, Linux, and various other platforms used across personal computers, servers, mobile devices, and embedded systems. The operating systems role as a core system component is critical to the functioning of modern computing environments.<SEP>Operating system is a system software that manages computer hardware and software resources, providing services for computer programs.<SEP>Operating System (OS) is a program collection that controls and manages hardware and software resources, organizes computer work, allocates resources, and provides convenient interfaces and environments for users and other software.

System Call Entry Table
The system call entry table is a data structure that maps system call numbers to their respective handler functions in the kernel.

Shared Resources
Shared resources such as storage, I/O devices, and files are managed by the operating system to ensure stability and security.<SEP>Shared resources are system assets that can be accessed by multiple concurrent processes, categorized into mutually exclusive and simultaneous access types.

Interrupt Instruction
An interrupt instruction causes a transition from user mode to kernel mode by invoking hardware and software mechanisms.

Program Counter
The program counter is a register that holds the address of the next instruction to be executed.<SEP>The Program Counter (PC) is a register that holds the address of the next instruction to be executed.<SEP>Program counter is a register that holds the address of the next instruction to be executed, preserved during interrupt or exception handling.

Privileged Instruction
A privileged instruction is a type of machine instruction that can only be executed in kernel mode.<SEP>Privileged instruction refers to a type of system command with the highest level of access, capable of affecting core system functions such as memory clearance, clock setting, system resource allocation, and user permission modification.

Trap Instruction
A trap instruction is a mechanism that triggers a system call, switching CPU state from user mode to kernel mode.<SEP>The Trap Instruction is a type of instruction executed in user mode that triggers a voluntary interrupt, leading the system to transition into kernel mode.

General-Purpose Registers
General-purpose registers are temporary storage locations used by the CPU during program execution.

Device Management
Device management involves operations such as device allocation, deallocation, and triggering device startup.<SEP>Device management ensures efficient handling of input/output operations by managing buffers, allocating devices, processing I/O requests, and enabling virtual devices.

Program Status Word
The program status word is a register that stores the current state of the processor, including flags and status bits.

Interrupt Return Instruction
An interrupt return instruction is used to switch back from kernel mode to user mode after handling a system call.<SEP>Interrupt return instruction is a CPU instruction used to return execution from a handler back to the interrupted program.

File Management
File management includes operations like file reading, writing, creation, and deletion.<SEP>File management oversees file storage space, directory systems, file reading and writing operations, and file protection within the operating system.

Process Control
Process control manages operations such as process creation, termination, blocking, and waking up.

Memory Management
Memory management involves memory allocation, deallocation, and retrieving memory usage details.<SEP>Memory management handles memory allocation and recycling, address mapping, protection, sharing, and extending memory capacity to support multiple programs efficiently.

Process Communication
Process communication enables message or signal exchange between processes.

Collaborative Task Execution
Collaborative task execution means that multiple computers in a distributed system can work together to accomplish a single task.

Distributed Operating System
A distributed operating system is an operating system designed to manage a distributed computer system, enabling coordinated operation among its component computers.

Communication
Communication refers to the exchange of information between any two computers in a distributed system.

Network Operating System
A network operating system is a system that integrates computers in a network to enable communication, data transfer, and resource sharing among them.

Distributed Computer System
A distributed computer system consists of multiple computers that communicate with each other, operate with equal status, share resources, allow subsystem formation and reconfiguration, and can collaboratively perform tasks in parallel.

Distribution
Distribution refers to the characteristic of a system where components and processing are spread across multiple computers.

Resource Sharing
Resource sharing is a feature where computing resources on each computer in a system are available to all users across the network.

Computer
A computer is a computing device that operates as part of a network or distributed system and contributes to system functions.<SEP>The computer is a machine composed of processing units, memory, devices, and files, operated by an operating system.

Non-Privileged Instruction
Non-privileged instruction is a type of command that does not have elevated system access and is safe for use by regular user programs.

Memory Clearance
Memory clearance is a privileged operation used to erase or reset system memory.

Interrupt
Interrupt is a signal generated when a user attempts to execute a privileged instruction in user mode, forcing a transition to kernel mode.<SEP>Interrupt, also known as external interrupt, is an event originating from outside CPU execution, typically used for input/output operations such as I/O completion or timer signals.

Exception
Exception is an unexpected condition during program execution that triggers a transition to kernel mode for handling.<SEP>Exception, also known as internal interrupt, is an event originating from within CPU instruction execution, such as illegal opcode, address overrun, arithmetic overflow, or page faults in virtual memory systems.

System Crash
System crash refers to the failure of a computing system due to improper use of privileged instructions.

Clock Setting
Clock setting is a privileged operation that adjusts the systems internal timekeeping mechanism.

User Access Permission Modification
User access permission modification is a privileged action that alters the level of access granted to users or processes.

Virtual Memory Segment Table Modification
Virtual memory segment table modification is a privileged operation that alters the structure guiding virtual-to-physical memory mapping.

System Resource Allocation
System resource allocation refers to the assignment of computing resources such as memory, CPU time, or I/O devices, performed only via privileged instructions.

Page Table Modification
Page table modification is a privileged operation involved in managing virtual memory paging.

CPU
CPU is the central processing unit that executes instructions and supports system modes such as user and kernel mode.<SEP>The CPU (Central Processing Unit) is the primary processor in a computer responsible for executing instructions.<SEP>The CPU is the central processing unit of a computer, responsible for executing instructions and managing overall system operations.<SEP>The CPU is the central processing unit responsible for executing instructions; during the manual operation stage, it often waited for human operations, reducing its effectiveness.

BIOS
BIOS (Basic Input/Output System) is a firmware interface that initializes hardware during the boot process.

Partition
A partition is a logical division of a hard disk used to organize and manage data storage.

Hard Disk
A hard disk is a storage device that stores data, including operating systems, in multiple partitions.

Boot Sequence
The boot sequence is a set of rules stored in CMOS that determines the order in which the computer attempts to boot from storage devices.

CMOS
CMOS (Complementary Metal-Oxide-Semiconductor) is a small memory chip that stores system configuration data, including boot settings.

ROM
ROM (Read-Only Memory) is a non-volatile memory that stores firmware, including the boot program.

Main Boot Record
The Main Boot Record (MBR) is a special sector at the beginning of a disk that contains code for loading the operating system.

Initialization Program
The initialization program is the first component of an operating system loaded into memory during boot.

POST
POST (Power-On Self-Test) is a diagnostic test run by the BIOS to check hardware functionality.

Startup Manager
The startup manager is a program located in the root directory of an active partition that loads and starts the operating system.

Partition Boot Record
The Partition Boot Record (PBR) is the first sector of a partition used to load the startup manager.

Hard Disk Partition Table
The hard disk partition table is a data structure stored in the MBR that describes the partitions on the disk.

Active Partition
An active partition is a partition marked as bootable, which contains the operating system to be loaded.

Interrupt Vector Table
The Interrupt Vector Table is a data structure in memory used by the BIOS to manage hardware interrupts.

External Storage Device
An external storage device is a peripheral storage unit connected to a computer, such as a USB drive or external hard drive.

Boot Process
The boot process is the sequence of events that occurs during startup to load the operating system.

Extended Machine
Extended Machine, also known as a virtual machine, is a conceptual computer system created by the operating system to provide enhanced functionality and usability over the bare machine.

Bare Machine
Bare Machine is a physical computer system without any software layer, consisting only of hardware components and forming the foundation of a computer system.

Computer Resource
Computer Resource refers to the fundamental components of a computer system, including processing time, memory, storage, and devices, which are managed by the operating system.

Virtual Machine
Virtual Machine is a software-based emulation of a physical computer system that runs programs and operating systems as if they were running on actual hardware.<SEP>A virtual machine is an abstract computing environment created using virtualization technology, simulating a complete computer system for running operating systems and applications.

User Interface
User Interface is a system that allows users to interact with a computer system, including both graphical and command-line forms.<SEP>The user interface allows users to interact with the operating system through command-line or graphical means, enabling control and execution of tasks.

Graphical User Interface
Graphical User Interface (GUI) is a visual way for users to interact with an operating system using elements like windows, icons, and menus, typically accessed via mouse and keyboard.<SEP>The graphical user interface provides a visual method for users to interact with the operating system using windows, icons, menus, and pointers.

Processing Time
Processing Time refers to the amount of time a processor spends executing tasks and is a critical computer resource managed by the operating system.

Memory
Memory is a computer resource that stores data and program instructions temporarily for quick access by the processor, managed by the operating system.<SEP>Memory refers to the computers primary storage, used to hold programs and data during execution.<SEP>Memory is a hardware resource that stores data and instructions temporarily for quick access by the processor.

Storage
Storage is a computer resource used for permanent or long-term data retention, such as hard drives and solid-state drives, managed by the operating system.

File
File is a collection of data stored on a computer system, managed by the operating system for creation, access, and deletion.

Device
Device refers to external hardware components such as keyboards, mice, printers, and network interfaces, which are controlled and managed by the operating system.

Processing Unit Management
Processing unit management involves managing processes or threads, including scheduling, synchronization, communication, and handling deadlocks in a multi-programming environment.

Command Interface
The command interface enables users to control job execution via typed commands, supporting both interactive (online) and batch (offline) modes.

Batch Command Interface
The batch command interface, also known as the offline command interface, processes jobs in sequence using pre-written job control instructions without real-time user interaction.

Interactive Command Interface
The interactive command interface, also known as the online command interface, allows real-time user interaction with the system through terminals or consoles.

Job
A job refers to a unit of work submitted to a computer system for execution, typically managed by the operating system.

Process
A process is an instance of a program in execution, managed by the operating system and sharing system resources.<SEP>A process is an instance of a program in execution, managed by the operating system to support concurrency and resource sharing.

Program Interface
The program interface consists of system calls used by developers to request services from the operating system, such as memory allocation or device access.

Multi-programming Environment
A multi-programming environment allows multiple programs to be loaded into main memory simultaneously, enabling concurrent execution.

Thread
A thread is a lightweight sub-process that shares memory and resources with other threads within the same process and is managed by the operating system.

Resource Management
Resource management involves coordinating and distributing system resources such as CPU, memory, and devices among various processes.<SEP>Resource Management refers to the processes by which the operating system controls access to and allocation of computing resources among various applications and users.

Hardware System
The hardware system refers to the physical components of a computer, including the processor, memory, input/output devices, and storage.

Computer System
The computer system refers to the integration of hardware and software components, including the processor, memory, input/output devices, and the operating system, forming a functional computing environment.<SEP>Computer System is a framework composed of hardware, operating system, applications, and users, functioning in a layered structure from bottom to top.

Multi-programming
Multi-programming is a technique that allows multiple programs to reside in main memory simultaneously, enabling concurrent execution and efficient resource utilization.

Worker
The worker represents the operating system, who performs tasks on behalf of the employer, manages system resources, and executes commands.

Interface
An interface is a means by which users or programs communicate with the operating system, either through commands or system calls.

Employer
The employer represents the user of the computer system who issues commands and relies on the operating system to execute tasks.

User
The interactive command interface allows users to input commands and receive immediate feedback from the operating system.<SEP>User is the individual who interacts with the computer system, relying on the operating system and applications to perform tasks.

Address Mapping
Memory management performs address mapping to translate logical addresses into physical memory locations, supporting virtual memory concepts.

Directory Management
File management includes directory management, which organizes files into hierarchical structures for easier access and navigation.

Buffering
Device management uses buffering to reduce the wait time for I/O operations by temporarily storing data between devices and the processor.

Processor Running Mode
Processor running mode refers to the operational state of a CPU, divided into user mode and kernel mode, determining the type of instructions that can be executed.

Operating System Kernel Program
The operating system kernel program is a management program responsible for controlling and supervising user applications, executing privileged instructions.

System Call Instruction
System call instruction, also known as a supervisor call, allows user programs to request services from the operating system while running in user mode.

Non-Privileged Instructions
Non-privileged instructions are safe commands that users can execute, limited to accessing their own address space without affecting system resources.

Privileged Instructions
Privileged instructions are system-level commands that only the kernel can execute; examples include I/O instructions, disabling interrupts, clearing memory, and modifying system registers.

Interrupt Switch
The interrupt switch is a conceptual hardware switch inside the CPU, where setting it to 0 enables kernel mode and setting it to 1 enables user mode.

User-Defined Program
A user-defined program, also known as an application, runs outside the operating system and cannot execute privileged instructions for security reasons.

Modern Operating System
A modern operating system is designed using layered architecture and structured programming principles, with functionality distributed across multiple layers.<SEP>Modern Operating System is an evolved OS design that widely adopts object-oriented technologies to improve correctness, reliability, and extensibility.

Layered Structure
Layered structure is a design approach in operating systems where functions are organized into distinct layers, each built on top of the layer below.

Interrupt Mechanism
Interrupt mechanism allows the CPU to respond to hardware events, improving CPU efficiency and supporting core system functions such as I/O handling and process scheduling.

Process Control Block
Process control block (PCB) is a data structure used by the operating system to track the state and attributes of a running process.

Primitive
A primitive is a low-level, atomic operation in the operating system kernel, designed to be indivisible and fast, used for critical system tasks such as process control and device management.

System Control Data Structure
System control data structures are used to maintain state information about system resources, including process control blocks, device control blocks, and memory allocation tables.

Clock Management
Clock management handles timekeeping and supports scheduling by generating time-based interrupts for task switching and system coordination.

Memory Allocation Table
Memory allocation table is a system data structure that tracks the usage and availability of memory regions.

Device Control Block
Device control block is a data structure used to manage and monitor the status and operation of a hardware device.

Job Control Block
Job control block is a data structure used to manage information about a job in batch processing systems.

Buffer
Buffer is a temporary storage area used for data transfer between different system components or during I/O operations.

Memory Protection Register
The memory protection register is a system register used to enforce memory access permissions, preventing unauthorized access to protected memory regions.

Program Status Word Register
The program status word register is a hardware register that stores the current state of the CPU, including flags and status bits that affect instruction execution.

Message Queue
Message queue is a data structure that stores messages for inter-process communication, enabling asynchronous data exchange.

Free Area Registration Table
Free area registration table is a data structure that records available memory segments for allocation.

Linked List
Linked list is a data structure used to organize and manage collections of system objects, such as processes or I/O requests.

Timekeeping
Clock management provides accurate system time and supports task scheduling through interrupts.

Atomic Operation
A primitive is implemented as an atomic operation to ensure that no interruption occurs during critical system actions.

Process Scheduling
Interrupt mechanism enables process scheduling by triggering context switches during I/O or time slices.

Process Management
Primitives are used in process management to ensure safe and synchronized execution of core operations.

I/O Handling
Interrupt mechanism improves CPU utilization by allowing it to execute other processes during I/O operations.

Knowledge Points
Knowledge Points refer to the essential topics and information within the Computer System Overview.

Computer System Overview
Computer System Overview is a foundational topic covering the key components and principles of computer systems.

Hybrid Kernel
Hybrid Kernel is a modern operating system design that combines advantages of macro and micro kernel architectures, integrating features from both to improve flexibility and performance.

iOS
iOS is a mobile operating system developed by Apple, based on macro kernel architecture.

macOS
macOS is an operating system developed by Apple, based on macro kernel architecture.

Android
Android is a mobile operating system developed by Google, based on macro kernel architecture.

Macro Kernel
Macro Kernel, also known as monolithic kernel or big kernel, is an operating system architecture where major system functionality modules run as a tightly integrated unit in kernel mode, providing high-performance system services.

Micro Kernel
Micro Kernel is an operating system architecture that moves non-core functions to user space, enabling easier system extension and reducing the need for kernel modifications.

Software Crisis
Software Crisis refers to the challenges in large-scale software development, including increasing complexity, maintenance difficulties, and scalability issues.

Fuchsia
Fuchsia is an operating system developed by Google, designed with a micro kernel architecture.

OS
OS is an operating system developed by Huawei, designed with a micro kernel architecture.

Virtualization
Virtualization refers to the technique of transforming a physical entity into multiple logical entities, allowing users to perceive multiple instances of a resource.

Mutual Exclusion
Mutual exclusion is a sharing method where a resource is accessible by only one process at a time, preventing data corruption or confusion during access.

Simultaneous Access
Simultaneous access allows multiple processes to use a resource over time, with the system managing access in a time-sliced manner, typically at a macro level.

Critical Resource
A critical resource is a system resource that can be accessed by only one process at a time, and its shared use requires careful coordination to avoid conflicts.<SEP>A critical resource is a system resource that must be accessed by only one process at a time to avoid conflicts, such as printers or tape drives.

Virtual Technology
Virtual technology is a set of techniques used to create logical representations of physical resources, such as processors, storage, and I/O devices.<SEP>Virtual technology is the implementation method used to achieve virtualization in operating systems, enabling logical abstraction of physical resources.

Tape Drive
A tape drive is a storage device used for sequential data access, typically requiring mutual exclusion during operation.

Multi-Programming Environment
A multi-programming environment is a computing setup where multiple programs reside in memory simultaneously, allowing the CPU to switch between them during I/O waits.

Time-Sharing
Time-sharing is a computing method where a single processor is shared among multiple users or processes in a round-robin fashion, creating the illusion of parallel execution.<SEP>Time-sharing is a technique used to enable concurrency by allocating CPU time slices among multiple processes in a single processor environment.

Printer
A printer is a physical output device that requires exclusive access to avoid mixed or corrupted print results.

I/O Device
An I/O device is a hardware component that facilitates input and output operations between a computer and external devices.

Disk Device
A disk device is a secondary storage medium that supports simultaneous access by multiple processes through time-sharing.

Reentrant Code
Reentrant code is a type of software that can be safely shared among multiple processes because it does not modify its own state.

Virtual Storage
Virtual storage is a logical extension of physical memory, created using virtual memory technology to increase the apparent size of available memory.

Virtual Device
A virtual device is a logical representation of a physical I/O device, enabling multiple users to share a single physical device simultaneously.

Asynchrony
Asynchrony is a fundamental characteristic of operating systems, referring to the unpredictable timing of events and the need for the system to handle them without assuming a fixed order or schedule.

Memory Capacity
Memory capacity refers to the total amount of data that can be stored in a system's memory, which can be logically expanded using virtual memory techniques.

Multitasking
Multitasking is a technique in operating systems that allows multiple programs to run concurrently by dividing processor time among them.

Virtual Processor
A virtual processor is a logical representation of a physical CPU created through time-sharing techniques, allowing multiple users to feel they have exclusive access to a processor.

Asynchronous Execution
Asynchronous execution describes the non-sequential and unpredictable progression of processes due to limited resources, leading to variable execution speeds.

Shared Device
A shared device is a physical I/O device that is made accessible to multiple users simultaneously through virtualization techniques.

Global Variable Access
Global variable access refers to the operation of reading from or writing to variables shared across multiple processes, which can lead to errors if not synchronized properly.

Physical Memory
The physical memory refers to the real, tangible memory hardware installed in a computer system.

Physical CPU
The physical CPU is the actual hardware processor in a computer system that performs computational tasks.

Processes
Concurrent processes access shared resources, requiring the operating system to manage access to prevent conflicts.

Physical I/O Device
A virtual device is a logical representation of a physical I/O device, enabling multiple logical instances from one physical unit.

Voluntary Interrupt
A Voluntary Interrupt is a self-initiated interruption of execution, caused by a program using a trap instruction to request OS services.

Privileged Operations
Privileged Operations are system-level tasks that can only be performed in kernel mode and are inaccessible to user programs directly.

Voluntary Entry to Kernel
Voluntary Entry to Kernel refers to the process by which a user program uses a trap instruction to transition into kernel mode for service requests.

Entry Address
The entry address refers to the starting address of a program or subroutine.

Interrupt Handling Program
The interrupt handling program is a software routine triggered by hardware interrupts.

Interrupt Request
An interrupt request is a signal sent to the processor to indicate that an external event requires immediate attention.<SEP>Interrupt request is a signal generated by hardware devices to request CPU attention, typically initiated via INTR or NMI lines.

CALL Instruction
The CALL instruction is used to invoke a subroutine, providing the address of the target subroutine.

Vector Address
The vector address is generated by the hardware vector method and used to locate the interrupt handling program's entry address.<SEP>Vector address is a memory location used in interrupt handling to determine the entry point of an interrupt handler.

Interrupt Priority Decision
Interrupt priority decision is the mechanism by which a processor selects between multiple simultaneous interrupt requests.

Hardware Circuit
A dedicated hardware circuit is required to implement the processing procedure.<SEP>Hardware circuit is a dedicated electronic system that enables interrupt handling, including interrupt vector generation and state switching.

Trap
Trap, also known as interrupt trap, is a software-initiated exception often used to invoke system calls or enable controlled transitions from user mode to kernel mode.

Maskable Interrupt
Maskable interrupt is a type of interrupt that can be disabled or ignored by the processor through interrupt masking mechanisms.

Non-Maskable Interrupt
Non-maskable interrupt is a high-priority interrupt that cannot be disabled and is used for critical hardware failures, such as power loss or system crashes.

Fault
Fault is a type of exception caused by an instruction execution issue, such as illegal opcode, division by zero, or page fault, typically recoverable.

Abort
Abort is a type of exception indicating a fatal hardware failure, such as memory parity error or controller malfunction, which prevents further execution.

Interrupt Handler
Interrupt handler is a routine executed by the CPU in response to an interrupt or exception, responsible for processing the event and returning control.

Floating-Point Unit
Floating-point unit is a specialized processor component for handling floating-point arithmetic operations.

N
N

Bare Metal
Bare metal refers to the physical hardware of a computer system without any operating system or virtualization layer.

Guest Operating System
A guest operating system is an operating system that runs inside a virtual machine and is managed by a hypervisor.

Second-Class Hypervisor
A second-class hypervisor is a program that runs on top of a host operating system and provides virtualization capabilities by managing virtual machines as processes.

Host Operating System
A host operating system is the underlying operating system that runs on the physical hardware and supports the operation of a second-class hypervisor.

First-Class Hypervisor
A first-class hypervisor is a virtual machine manager that runs directly on bare metal, operates at the highest privilege level, and provides multiple virtual machines that are exact replicas of the physical hardware.

Virtualization Technology
Virtualization technology enables the creation of multiple virtual machines from a single physical machine by abstracting and managing hardware resources.

Virtual Machine Manager
A virtual machine manager, or hypervisor, is responsible for creating, managing, and monitoring virtual machines on a physical host.

Virtual Kernel Mode
Virtual kernel mode is the state in which a guest operating system believes it is running in kernel mode, though it is actually running under the supervision of a hypervisor.

Web Hosting
Web hosting is a service that provides storage and access to web content, where virtualization enables efficient resource utilization and flexible deployment.

X86 Platform
The X86 platform refers to a family of instruction set architectures developed by Intel and AMD, commonly used in personal computers and servers.

Virtualization Support
Virtualization support refers to CPU features that enable efficient and secure execution of virtual machines by allowing direct hardware access while maintaining isolation.

VMware Workstation
VMware Workstation is a second-class hypervisor that enables running multiple virtual machines on a host operating system such as Windows or Linux.

Virtual Disk
A virtual disk is a file on the host system that emulates a physical hard drive for a virtual machine.

Hardware Abstraction
Hardware abstraction is the technique of hiding the physical characteristics of a computing platform to provide a consistent and unified interface for virtual machines.

Cloud Host
A cloud host is a virtual machine offered by a service provider, allowing users to rent computing resources with full control over the operating system and software while paying a lower cost than physical servers.

Sensitive Instruction
A sensitive instruction is a type of CPU instruction that can affect system-wide state and is restricted to kernel mode, requiring special handling in virtualized environments.

Guest Process
A guest process is a user-level process running inside a virtual machine, which believes it is executing in user mode.

Bare Metal Architecture
Bare metal architecture refers to the design where a first-class hypervisor runs directly on physical hardware without an intermediate host operating system.

Cloud Hosting
Cloud hosting is a service model where virtual machines are rented to users, allowing them to run their own operating systems and software with lower costs than physical servers.

Nested Virtualization
Nested virtualization is a capability that allows a virtual machine to run a hypervisor inside it, enabling multiple layers of virtualization.

Nested Hypervisor
Nested hypervisor refers to a scenario where a hypervisor runs inside another hypervisor, often creating a system of layered virtual machines.

Soft Real-Time System
A soft real-time system allows occasional violations of timing constraints without causing permanent damage, such as in airline reservation systems or banking management systems.

Hard Real-Time System
A hard real-time system requires absolute guarantees that certain actions occur precisely within a specified time frame, such as in aircraft flight control systems.

Banking Management System
A banking management system is a soft real-time system that can tolerate small timing violations without irreversible consequences.

Flight Control System
A flight control system is a critical application of a hard real-time system, requiring guaranteed response within strict time limits.

Time Constraint
A time constraint is a deadline or time window that must be met for a task to be considered successful.

Airline Reservation System
An airline reservation system is an example of a soft real-time system where minor delays are permissible.

Real-Time Operating System
A real-time operating system is designed to handle tasks with strict timing constraints, ensuring timely execution without time-slice queuing.

External Signal
An external signal is an input to a real-time operating system requiring immediate processing within a tight time limit.

Timeliness
Timeliness is a primary characteristic of real-time operating systems, ensuring tasks are completed within their specified deadlines.

Reliability
Reliability is a critical feature of real-time operating systems, ensuring consistent and predictable performance under time constraints.<SEP>Reliability is the degree to which a system or component performs its required functions under stated conditions for a specified period of time.<SEP>Reliability is the ability of an operating system to perform consistently and stably under various conditions.
Human-machine contradiction refers to the growing disparity between the speed of computer hardware and the slower manual operations performed by users, leading to inefficiency.

The manual operation stage refers to a phase in computing history where all tasks, including program loading, execution, and result output, required human intervention, and no operating system was present.
The computer is the machine that performs the computational tasks during the manual operation stage, requiring human intervention for all operations.
Resource utilization refers to the efficiency of using computer resources, which was low during the manual operation stage due to exclusive user access.<SEP>CPUI/O

Program loading is the task of transferring a program into memory for execution, requiring manual intervention during the manual operation stage.
Result output involves the presentation of computational results, which during the manual operation stage required manual handling.
A high-speed machine is a proposed solution to replace slower manual operations, improving control over jobs and reducing CPU idle time.
Job control refers to the management of computational jobs; during the manual operation stage, it required manual steps, leading to inefficiencies.

Operating System Portability
Operating system portability refers to the ease with which an operating system can be adapted to run on different hardware platforms.

Frequent Context Switching
Frequent context switching refers to the repeated transition between kernel mode and user mode, which increases execution overhead in microkernel systems.

Hardware Platform
The hardware platform refers to the physical computing infrastructure, including processors and peripheral devices, upon which an operating system runs.

System Performance
System performance refers to the efficiency and responsiveness of an operating system under various workloads and operational conditions.

Microkernel Structure
The microkernel structure is an architectural approach where core operating system services are run in a minimal kernel, and other services are implemented in user space.

Message Passing Mechanism
The message passing mechanism is a communication paradigm used between processes or systems, where data is exchanged via messages for coordination and information transfer.<SEP>The message passing mechanism is a communication method used between clients and servers or between servers in a microkernel system to exchange data and commands.

Distributed Computing
Distributed computing involves multiple computing systems communicating and coordinating their actions to achieve a common goal.

Kernel
The kernel is the central component of an operating system that manages system resources, hardware communication, and process execution.

System Services
System services are functional components of an operating system that manage tasks such as file handling, memory allocation, and process scheduling.

Industrial Applications
Industrial applications involve the use of computing systems in manufacturing and process automation, demanding high reliability and robustness.

Macrokernel
The macrokernel is an alternative operating system architecture in which most operating system services run in kernel space, enabling faster execution but reduced modularity.

Military Applications
Military applications involve the use of computing systems in defense and combat operations, requiring extreme reliability and security.

Microkernel
The microkernel is a minimalist kernel design that holds only the most essential operating system functions, while other functionalities are moved to user space as independent servers.

Real-Time Applications
Real-time applications require predictable and timely responses, making them critical in fields like industrial control and aviation.

Aerospace Applications
Aerospace applications refer to computing systems used in aviation and space technology, where system failure is unacceptable.

Virtual Memory Server
The virtual memory server is a user-mode server responsible for implementing virtual memory management, including page allocation and replacement.

Low-Level Memory Management
Low-level memory management includes hardware-dependent tasks such as logical-to-physical address translation and page table handling, located in the microkernel.

Mechanism and Policy Separation
Mechanism and policy separation is a design principle in microkernel systems that places foundational mechanisms in the kernel and policy decisions in user-mode servers.<SEP>Mechanism and policy separation is a design principle where mechanisms (implementation of functionality) are separated from policies (decision-making rules for how to use the mechanism).

Server Process
A server process is a user-space program that implements OS functionalities such as process management, memory management, and I/O handling.

Hardware-Dependent Code
Hardware-dependent code comprises system-level functions tied to specific hardware, such as interrupt handling and address translation, located in the microkernel.

Process Management Server
The process management server is a user-mode server responsible for managing processes and threads, including scheduling, switching, and synchronization.

System Reliability
System reliability refers to the ability of a microkernel system to maintain operation even when individual server processes fail.

System Flexibility
System flexibility allows for easy modification and extension of functionality by updating or adding user-mode servers without modifying the kernel.

System Portability
System portability enables the operating system to be adapted to new hardware platforms with minimal changes due to modular design.

Distributed Computing Support
Distributed computing support allows microkernel systems to operate across networked or distributed environments using message passing.

Interrupt and Exception Handling
Interrupt and exception handling refers to the microkernel's responsibility for capturing hardware interrupts and software exceptions, then forwarding them to appropriate user-mode servers for processing.

Performance Overhead
Performance overhead refers to the reduced efficiency caused by the increased number of context switches and inter-process communication in microkernel systems.

Central Processor
Central Processor is a key hardware component responsible for executing instructions and handling data processing.

Software
Software is the overarching category of programs that instruct computers on what to do, with the operating system being its core component.

Hardware
Hardware includes central processors, memory, input/output devices, and provides fundamental computing resources.

Application
Application refers to software such as word processors, spreadsheet programs, compilers, and web browsers that define how computing resources are used to solve user problems.

Input/Output Device
Input/Output Devices facilitate data exchange between the computer and external environment, such as keyboards, displays, and printers.

System Software
System Software is the foundational software layer of a computer system, with the operating system being the most basic and essential component.

Computer Composition Principle
Computer Composition Principle is a methodological framework for structuring computer systems into hierarchical layers, distinct from the layered division mentioned in the text.

Computation Resource
Computation Resource includes processing power, storage capacity, and bandwidth necessary for running tasks and applications.

Informational Era
The Informational Era refers to the modern period characterized by the widespread use of digital technology and reliance on software, where software is considered the soul of computer systems.

Traditional OS
Traditional OS is an operating system architecture where mechanisms are located in lower kernel layers and policies in higher layers.

Client Server Model
The client-server model is a communication paradigm in microkernel OS where services run as servers and clients request them through message passing.

Small Kernel
A small kernel is a design principle in microkernel OS where the core functionality is minimized to enhance reliability and maintainability.

Microkernel Structure OS
Microkernel Structure OS is an operating system design that emphasizes a minimal kernel and modular architecture.

Mechanism
Mechanism refers to the specific execution components that implement a particular function in an operating system.

Policy
Policy refers to the high-level decisions and parameters that determine how a mechanism is used to achieve specific goals.

Object-Oriented Technology
Object-oriented technology is a programming paradigm that uses abstraction, encapsulation, and inheritance to manage system complexity and improve design reliability.

Extensibility
Extensibility is the capacity of an operating system to be easily modified or expanded with new features.

Inheritance
Inheritance is a mechanism in object-oriented technology that allows classes to derive properties and behaviors from other classes.

Encapsulation
Encapsulation is a principle that bundles data and methods together and restricts access to internal components.

Correctness
Correctness is the property of an operating system ensuring it operates as intended without errors.

Abstraction
Abstraction is a principle in object-oriented technology that hides complex implementation details and exposes only essential features.

System Complexity
System complexity refers to the challenge of managing large, interconnected components within an operating system.
